05483nam a22007815i 9781646021536DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9781646021536  a(DE-B1597)600784  a(OCoLC)1273974355  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBL65.G4bR46 2016eb 7aHIS0260302bisacsh04a299/.2122300aAs Above, So Below :bReligion and Geography /ced. by Shana Zaia, Gina Konstantopoulos. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b12 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRencontre Assyriologique Internationale00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tEditors’ Introduction -- tChapter 1. Gods in the Margins: Religion, Kingship, and the Fictionalized Frontier -- tChapter 2. Place and Portability: Divine Emblems in Old Babylonian Law -- tChapter 3. Mari’s Investiture Scene and the Visualization of Kingship in the Old Babylonian Period -- tChapter 4. Divine Foundations: Religion and Assyrian Capital Cities -- tChapter 5. Approaches to the Religious Topography of the Oasis of Taymāʾ, Northwest Arabia, During the First Millennium BCE: Images, Texts, and Space -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume addresses the nexus of religion and geography in the ancient Near East through case studies of various time periods and regions. Using Sumerian, Akkadian, and Aramaic text corpora, iconography, and archaeological evidence, the contributors illuminate the diverse phenomena that occur when religion is viewed through the lenses of space and place. Gina Konstantopoulos draws upon Sumerian literature to understand mythicized and semimythicized locations. Seth Richardson and Elizabeth Knott focus on the Old Babylonian period, with Richardson addressing the interplay between law, location, and the gods, while Knott turns from text to image, relocating the reader to Syria and realizing the potential of royal iconography when situated in the “right” space. Shana Zaia moves forward to the first millennium, following the capital of the Neo-Assyrian Empire as it shifted from city to city, with divine implications. Finally, Arnulf Hausleiter and Sebastiano Lora focus on northwest Arabia, unearthing a local pantheon and situating it among the various influences in the region from the second millennium onward. Covering a broad geographical and temporal scope while maintaining a cohesive focus on the theme, this book will appeal especially to Assyriologists, scholars of the ancient Near East, and specialists in historical geography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aReligion and geographyvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Iraq.2bisacsh1 aHausleiter, Arnulf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnott, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonstantopoulos, Gina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonstantopoulos, Gina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLora, Sebastiano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZaia, Shana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZaia, Shana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08